{
  "doc_id": "16892",
  "text": "Our results showed that the frequency of ritual interactions, but not agonistic interactions, was influenced by the hierarchy. Similarly, in Przewalski's horse natural populations, lower-ranking stallions have been shown to engage more often in rituals than higher-ranking ones, which could indicate that they have a tendency for compromising rather than fighting [CITATION_1] . Highranking stallions win more fights, but do not to display higher rates of physical aggression than other males [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . This suggests that the dominance rank of high-ranking males is rarely challenged. Threats, olfactory cues and vocal cues may suffice to maintain their dominance rank. Tilson et al. [CITATION_4] found that conflict for rank was limited to the three lower-ranking Przewalski's stallions, within a group of eight bachelors. Because mutual assessments are more frequent when the degree of asymmetry in fighting abilities between two individuals is low [CITATION_5] , these results suggest that the degree of asymmetry in fighting abilities is generally lower at the bottom of the hierarchy, or in our 2010 group, within the stallions that were ranked 2-4.",
